    "text": "Here are summaries of recent articles on agentic AI security:\n\n*OWASP AI Agent Security Cheat Sheet:*\nThis cheat sheet provides best practices for securing AI agent architectures and minimizing attack surfaces. It highlights key risks such as prompt injection, tool abuse, data exfiltration, memory poisoning, and excessive autonomy. It offers guidance on tool security, input validation, memory security, human-in-the-loop controls, output validation, monitoring, multi-agent security, and data protection.\nSource: <https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/AI_Agent_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html>\n\n*Secure AI agents at scale using Microsoft Agent 365:*\nThis article discusses how Microsoft Agent 365 provides a unified control plane for overseeing the security of AI agents in an organization. It integrates with Microsoft’s security suite to secure agents built in Microsoft Copilot Studio, Microsoft Foundry, and third-party solutions. The article outlines core security capabilities, including identity management, access control, security posture management, threat detection and response, runtime defense, and data security.\nSource: <https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/security/security-for-ai/agent-365-security>\n\n*Agentic AI Security: What It Is and How to Do It - Palo Alto Networks:*\nThis article defines agentic AI security as the protection of AI agents that can plan, act, and make decisions autonomously. It discusses the security implications of agentic AI, including new security challenges related to reasoning paths, memory poisoning, tool use, and interactions between agents. The article also covers top agentic AI security threats and how to secure agentic AI systems.\nSource: <https://www.paloaltonetworks.com/cyberpedia/what-is-agentic-ai-security>\n\n*AI agent security: How to protect digital sidekicks (and your business) | Google Cloud Blog:*\nThis blog post discusses the importance of AI agent security, highlighting the potential risks of compr